### <a id="v1.3.0-beta1-upgrade"></a>Upgrade Path

The supported upgrade paths to PKS v1.3.0-beta.1 are from PKS v1.2.0 and later.

For more information, see [Upgrading PKS](upgrade-pks.html) and [Upgrading PKS with NSX-T](upgrade-pks-nsxt.html).

### <a id="v1.3.0-beta1-whats-new"></a>What's New

PKS v1.3.0-beta.1 adds the following:

- Beta support for Azure. For more information, see [Azure](azure-index.html).
- BOSH Backup and Restore (BBR) for single-master clusters.
- Routable pods on NSX-T.
- Large size NSX-T load balancers.
- NSX-T proxy support.
- Sink resources in internetless environments.
- Support for Multiple T0 NSX-T routers.
- Smoke tests.
- Support for scaling down the number of worker nodes.
- Support for defining the CIDR range for Kubernetes pods on Flannel networks.
- **Bug Fix**: The **No proxy** property for vSphere now accepts wildcard domains like
`*.example.com` and `example.com`. See [Networking](./installing-pks-vsphere.html#networking) in
_Installing PKS on vSphere_ for more information.

### <a id="v1.3.0-beta1-known-issues"></a>Known Issues

PKS v1.3.0-beta.1 has the following known issues:

####<a id="azure-orange-config"></a> Azure Incomplete Configuration

When deploying PKS to Azure with Ops Manager, the PKS tile remains orange 
even though service plan configuration is complete. 
The orange color status indicates that PKS needs additional configuration and cannot be deployed. 

**Workaround**: Select a non-default VM type for the VMs listed for each service plan. 
Then save your changes and deploy.

####<a id="cves"></a> Security Known Issues

* [CVE-2018-15759](https://pivotal.io/security/cve-2018-15759): This CVE contains an insecure method of verifying credentials. A remote unauthenticated malicious user may make many requests to the service broker with a series of different credentials, allowing them to infer valid credentials and gain access to perform broker operations.
* [CVE-2018-1002105](https://pivotal.io/security/cve-2018-1002105): This CVE enables users to establish a connection through the Kubernetes API server to back-end servers, and then send arbitrary requests over the same connection directly to the back end. These requests are authenticated with the Kubernetes API serverâ€™s TLS credentials used to establish the back end connection.

<p class="note warning"><strong>WARNING</strong>: Because of these two CVE issues, we recommend PKS v1.3.0-beta.1 for testing purposes only. <b>This beta release should not be deployed into production environments.</b></p>
